% ============================================================
\begin{abstract}
% ============================================================
Training medical AI agents through multi-turn reinforcement learning is fundamentally unstable. Response lengths explode to the generation limit as sparse terminal rewards incentivize verbosity over structured reasoning; multi-turn tool-use collapses into single-turn monologues; and on-policy distillation---effective for stabilizing single-turn reasoning---fails to prevent monotonic decline in agentic settings, where trajectory diversity causes the teacher to become stale far faster than in closed-form QA. We propose \emph{Turn-Level Truncated On-Policy Distillation} (TT-OPD), a teacher-student co-evolution framework that resolves these compounding failure modes. An EMA-updated teacher conditions on outcome-privileged information---correctness signals injected into its context but withheld from the student---providing dense, outcome-aware KL regularization at every conversation turn rather than only at episode termination. Combined with cosine length-controlled reward, TT-OPD achieves 61.1\% validation accuracy (+8.5 pp over baseline) while sustaining multi-turn tool use (7.0--7.4 turns) and controlled response length (5.7--9.3K tokens) across 60 training steps; standard GRPO produces no improvement under identical conditions. We ground these experiments in \gym{}, a Gymnasium-compatible environment spanning 10 clinical domains with 195K+ tasks, 187+ domain-specific tools, and 828K medical passages. Our environment and training pipeline are publicly available.

\end{abstract}

% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
% ============================================================

Training language model agents through multi-turn reinforcement learning faces a fundamental instability problem. In agentic settings---where models interact with tools over multiple conversation turns---standard RL produces three compounding failure modes: (1) \emph{response explosion}, where outputs grow monotonically to the generation limit; (2) \emph{multi-turn collapse}, where the model degenerates from structured tool-use dialogues into single-turn verbosity; and (3) \emph{distillation instability}, where on-policy distillation (OPD)---effective for stabilizing single-turn reasoning~\citep{zhao26opsd, yang26rlsd}---fails to prevent monotonic decline in multi-turn agentic training.

We hypothesize that these failure modes share a common root cause: the mismatch between sparse terminal reward and the sequential structure of agentic trajectories. \emph{Response explosion} arises because the reward signal is delivered only at episode termination, incentivizing the model to maximize token-level coverage as a proxy for task completion---producing longer responses that are more likely to contain the correct answer somewhere, even at the cost of coherence. \emph{Multi-turn collapse} follows naturally: since single-turn verbosity is easier to optimize than coordinated multi-step tool use (which requires learning a latent turn-taking policy), the model converges toward monologue-style responses that bypass the tool interface entirely. \emph{Distillation instability} is exacerbated in agentic settings because trajectory diversity---the combinatorial space of tool-call sequences---causes the teacher to become stale orders of magnitude faster than in single-turn reasoning, where the output space is comparatively constrained. We validate each of these hypotheses through controlled ablations in Section~\ref{sec:analysis}.

These challenges are particularly acute in medical AI, where clinical reasoning requires gathering patient information, ordering tests, interpreting results, and making safe treatment decisions through multi-step tool-use interactions~\citep{nori2023gpt4, singhal2023medpalm2}. Recent work has explored training medical agents through RL~\citep{medagentgym2026, schmidgall2025agentclinic}, but existing approaches focus on narrow domains, lack safety-aware rewards, and do not address the training instability inherent to multi-turn agentic RL.

We introduce \gym{}, a Gymnasium-compatible environment spanning 10 clinical domains with 195K+ tasks, and propose \emph{Turn-Level Truncated On-Policy Distillation} (TT-OPD) to address the instability problem. Our contributions are:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Turn-Level Truncated On-Policy Distillation (TT-OPD).} A teacher-student co-evolution framework for stable multi-turn agentic RL. The teacher evolves alongside the student via EMA updates and conditions on outcome-privileged information---correctness signals injected into the teacher's context but absent from the student's---to provide dense, outcome-aware KL regularization at every conversation turn. Combined with cosine length-controlled reward, TT-OPD achieves 61.1\% validation accuracy (+8.5 pp) with sustained multi-turn tool use (7.0--7.4 turns) and controlled response length (5.7--9.3K tokens) over 60 steps, while standard GRPO shows no improvement.

    \item \textbf{Systematic OPD Failure Analysis.} Through four ablation variants (frozen teacher, hard-copy self-distillation, EMA-only, EMA + privileged conditioning without length control), we trace the failure progression from KL collapse to response explosion, identifying multi-turn collapse as an \emph{agentic-specific} failure mode absent from single-turn OPD settings~\citep{yang26rlsd, zhao26opsd}.

    \item \textbf{Multi-Domain Medical Gymnasium.} A unified environment spanning 10 clinical domains with 195K+ tasks, 187+ domain-specific tools, a knowledge-grounded retrieval system over 828K passages, and a safety-aware 5D reward function.

    \item \textbf{Agentic-Textual Transfer Gap.} We show that agentic RL teaches procedural competence (+22\% composite reward) but does not transfer to text QA due to format reward dilution (24:1 ratio), and that reward normalization (Dr.~GRPO) is the only mechanism producing meaningfully different dynamics.
\end{enumerate}

% ============================================================
\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}
% ============================================================

\paragraph{Medical LLMs and Benchmarks.}
Medical question answering has been extensively studied through benchmarks such as MedQA~\citep{jin2021medqa}, MedMCQA~\citep{pal2022medmcqa}, and PubMedQA~\citep{jin2019pubmedqa}. Large models including GPT-4~\citep{nori2023gpt4}, Med-PaLM 2~\citep{singhal2023medpalm2}, and HuatuoGPT-II~\citep{chen2024huatuogpt} have achieved impressive results. However, these benchmarks evaluate passive knowledge rather than agentic clinical competence.

\paragraph{Medical AI Agents.}
AgentClinic~\citep{schmidgall2025agentclinic} simulates patient-doctor interactions for diagnostic reasoning, but is limited to a single diagnostic domain and does not support multi-domain tool use, safety-aware rewards, or RL-based training---restricting its utility as a training environment for generalizable medical agents. MedAgentGym~\citep{medagentgym2026} provides a Gymnasium interface for training medical agents with RL, though its tool system is code-centric (Python execution sandboxes) rather than clinical tool-use (ordering labs, computing severity scores), limiting ecological validity for clinical deployment. MediX-R1~\citep{medixr1} applies GRPO to medical reasoning. MedOpenClaw~\citep{shen2025medopenclaw} provides an auditable runtime for medical imaging agents reasoning over full 3D studies, revealing a ``tool-use paradox'' where adding professional tools \emph{degrades} performance due to spatial grounding failures in volumetric navigation---a finding that directly supports our hypothesis that tool-use competence requires RL training rather than mere prompting, and motivates the structured tool curriculum in \gym{}. Our work differs by providing a unified multi-domain \emph{training} environment with safety-aware rewards and anti-collapse training.

\paragraph{Reinforcement Learning for LLMs.}
GRPO~\citep{shao2024deepseekmath} eliminates the need for a separate critic model by using group relative rewards. GSPO~\citep{gspo2025} introduces sequence-level importance sampling to reduce variance. DAPO~\citep{dapo2025} proposes dynamic sampling that filters out prompts where all rollouts succeed or all fail (avoiding zero-gradient updates), and introduces asymmetric clipping ranges ($\epsilon_{\text{low}} < \epsilon_{\text{high}}$) that encourage exploration by allowing larger probability increases than decreases. Dr.~GRPO~\citep{liu2025drgrpo} removes length normalization bias. However, these methods are designed and evaluated for single-turn reasoning; we show that in multi-turn agentic settings with online single-iteration GRPO, the importance ratio $\pi_\theta/\pi_\text{old} \equiv 1.0$ at every update, rendering DAPO's asymmetric clipping and GSPO's importance sampling \emph{vacuous}---the clip boundaries are never reached and the importance weights are identically one. Only Dr.~GRPO's per-token reward normalization, which operates on the advantage computation rather than the policy ratio, produces meaningfully different training dynamics.

\paragraph{On-Policy Distillation.}
On-policy distillation (OPD) trains a student model using its own trajectories with a teacher providing soft supervision. OPSD~\citep{zhao26opsd} introduces the foundational framework where a single model serves as both teacher and student via asymmetric context: the teacher conditions on privileged information (\eg{}, verified reasoning traces) while the student sees only the question. Self-Distilled RLVR~\citep{yang26rlsd} demonstrates that pure OPSD causes \emph{information leakage} and unstable long-term training, and proposes decoupling update \emph{direction} (from RLVR) and \emph{magnitude} (from self-distillation)---a decomposition that our TT-OPD instantiates differently via EMA for magnitude control and outcome-privileged conditioning for directional signal. SRPO~\citep{li26srpo} unifies group-relative and self-distillation objectives via sample routing. CRISP~\citep{sang26crisp} applies OPD for reasoning compression with periodic teacher refresh. \citet{song26opdsurvey} provide a comprehensive survey identifying \emph{agent-level} OPD as an open problem. Our TT-OPD addresses this open problem, extending OPD to multi-turn agentic settings where response explosion and multi-turn collapse---failure modes absent from single-turn reasoning---require additional stabilization mechanisms.

\paragraph{Privileged Information and Agentic RL.}
HiLL~\citep{xia26hill} addresses GRPO's \emph{advantage collapse} problem---when all rollouts receive the same reward, the group yields zero gradient---by co-training an adaptive hint policy alongside the reasoner, with a transfer-weighted reward that favors hints whose benefit transfers to the no-hint policy. While HiLL trains a separate policy network for hint generation, our privileged conditioning is template-based and injected only into the teacher's context for KL computation, never seen by the student. Complementary RL~\citep{muhtar26complementaryrl} proposes co-evolving an experience extractor with the actor in agentic RL, sharing our insight that agentic tasks benefit from auxiliary learning signals beyond sparse rewards. D$^2$Skill~\citep{tu26d2skill} introduces a dual-granularity skill bank for agentic RL that decomposes complex tasks into reusable primitives. Unlike these approaches, which focus on single-turn reasoning or task decomposition, TT-OPD addresses the specific challenge of \emph{multi-turn} agentic training where reward is sparse and diluted by format compliance, providing dense outcome-privileged supervision at every conversation turn.

\paragraph{Tool-Use and Retrieval-Augmented Generation.}
Tool-augmented LLMs~\citep{schick2024toolformer, qin2023toolllm} learn to invoke external APIs. In medicine, retrieval from knowledge bases improves factual grounding~\citep{xiong2024medcpt}. \gym{} integrates tool use with domain-specific medical knowledge retrieval as a core training mechanism.


