Three properties distinguish this training dynamic from standard RL:

\textbf{Oscillating recovery (TT-OPD effect).} Validation accuracy follows a sawtooth pattern: rising peaks (steps 15, 25, 30, 45, 60) interspersed with periodic dips (steps 20, 35, 50). This reflects the interplay between student drift and EMA teacher updates---the student explores beyond the teacher between updates, then the teacher catches up via EMA, re-anchoring the student. Crucially, each peak exceeds the previous one because the outcome-privileged conditioning makes the KL target richer than generic regularization: the teacher differentially reinforces correct reasoning and corrects incorrect reasoning at every turn.

\textbf{Response length control (cosine reward effect).} The cosine reward maintains response length between 5.7--9.3K tokens with clip ratios of 33--71\%, in sharp contrast to standard agentic RL where response length monotonically increases to the 12,288-token limit (91.7\% clipping by step 40 without cosine reward). The oscillating pattern (peaks at steps 10, 35 followed by compressions at steps 30, 40) indicates the model alternates between exploration and consolidation of multi-turn tool-use behavior.

\textbf{Sustained multi-turn structure (TT-OPD + cosine interaction).} Validation turns remain stable at 7.0--7.4 throughout training, confirming the model maintains its multi-turn tool-use behavior rather than degenerating into single-turn verbosity. This results from the interaction between turn-level KL regularization (which penalizes deviation from the teacher's turn-by-turn behavior) and the cosine length reward (which penalizes long single-turn responses). Standard GRPO, which lacks both per-turn regularization and length control, fails to preserve multi-turn structure.


\subsection{Benchmark Suite}
\label{sec:benchmarks}

We evaluate across 21 medical benchmarks spanning four categories: text QA (8 benchmarks including MedQA, MedMCQA, and 6 MMLU subsets), vision QA (6 benchmarks including VQA-RAD, SLAKE, and PathVQA), long-form QA (5 benchmarks including HealthSearchQA and MedicationQA), and EHR reasoning (MIMIC-III and eICU). Full benchmark details are provided in Appendix~\ref{app:benchmarks}.


\subsection{Experimental Setup}
\label{sec:setup}

\paragraph{Models and Training.} We use Qwen3.5-9B as the base model for TT-OPD training, alongside Lingshu-7B (a medical domain-adapted VLM based on Qwen2.5-VL-7B) and Qwen2.5-VL-7B-Instruct as baselines. Training uses 800 tasks from the bioagents\_medical distribution with learning rate $5 \times 10^{-7}$, 8 generations per prompt, KL penalty $\beta{=}0.01$, temperature 0.7, EMA decay $\alpha{=}0.995$, cosine reward ceiling $R_{\text{max}}{=}1.1$, and maximum context length $L_{\text{max}}{=}12{,}288$ tokens. All experiments run on 8$\times$NVIDIA A100 80GB GPUs. We verify zero data contamination between training data and all test benchmarks using test-set fingerprinting~\citep{yang2023rethinking}.


\subsection{Main Results}
\label{sec:results}

Across 3 seeds and up to 350 RL steps, standard agentic RL (GRPO) produces no text QA improvement: MedQA accuracy remains within a 0.6 pp band (60.4--61.0\%), statistically indistinguishable from the SFT baseline (60.7\%). In contrast, Dr.~GRPO achieves 61.8\% (+1.1 pp) at step 800, and direct QA RL (H12) reaches 62.4\% (+1.7 pp). Full per-checkpoint results and visualizations are provided in Appendix~\ref{app:rl_baselines}.

\subsection{Domain-Specific Performance}
\label{sec:domain_results}

Table~\ref{tab:domain_results} presents the agentic evaluation using the composite wrapper reward (mean of process quality, accuracy, format, safety, coherence scores). We report the eval wrapper reward at the start and best checkpoint for two training configurations: single-domain agentic RL (6 domains) and GSPO+DAPO v2 (combined 6-domain).

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Agentic competence: eval wrapper reward trajectory. Both configurations show clear improvement in procedural competence, with the combined GSPO+DAPO v2 achieving higher absolute scores due to its broader domain coverage.}
\label{tab:domain_results}
