\toprule
\textbf{Configuration} & \textbf{Domains} & \textbf{Initial} & \textbf{Best} & \textbf{$\Delta$} \\
\midrule
Agentic RL & 6 & 0.301 & 0.366 & +21.6\% \\
GSPO+DAPO v2 & 6 & 0.512 & 0.570 & +11.3\% \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}


% ============================================================
\section{Analysis}
\label{sec:analysis}
% ============================================================

\subsection{The Agentic-Textual Transfer Gap}
\label{sec:transfer}

Across 16 RL checkpoints (3 seeds $\times$ up to 7 steps), agentic RL produces no text QA transfer: MedQA accuracy remains within a 0.6 pp band (60.4--61.0\%), statistically indistinguishable from the SFT baseline. The absence of transfer stems from a confluence of factors that jointly suppress the accuracy gradient signal. In online single-iteration GRPO, the importance ratio $\pi_\theta/\pi_\text{old} \equiv 1.0$ because rollouts are always generated from the current policy, rendering all clipping innovations vacuous---the clip boundaries are never reached. Simultaneously, a conservative learning rate yields near-zero policy change per step (KL $< 0.001$), and the 5D reward composition creates a 24:1 format-to-accuracy ratio that drowns out the accuracy signal in the group-relative advantage computation.

Crucially, this transfer gap reflects reward dilution rather than a fundamental inability of RL to teach factual knowledge. Our H5 ablation, which uses accuracy as the sole reward signal, achieves +1.3 pp MedQA improvement, demonstrating that the model \emph{can} learn declarative knowledge through RL when the gradient is not diluted by format compliance. This reveals a \emph{procedural-declarative dissociation}: standard agentic RL improves procedural knowledge (+22\% composite reward for tool-use competence) without immediately changing declarative knowledge, paralleling neurological distinctions in cognitive science~\citep{squire2004memory}. The dissociation is an artifact of reward composition, not a fundamental limitation---Dr.~GRPO, which implicitly rebalances the format-to-accuracy ratio via per-token normalization, begins transferring by step 800 (MedQA 61.8\%, +1.1 pp). Full analysis with 5D reward trajectories and radar charts is provided in Appendix~\ref{app:procedural}.

\subsection{Training Dynamics Analysis}
\label{sec:dynamics}

Beyond the aggregate transfer gap, the \emph{dynamics} of TT-OPD training reveal distinctive patterns that shed light on how the method achieves stability. The most striking phenomenon is an \emph{oscillating recovery} pattern: validation accuracy does not improve monotonically but instead exhibits periodic dips of 2--4 pp followed by recovery to new highs. This pattern emerges consistently across seeds once EMA teacher updates are introduced (v14 onward) and is absent under hard-copy teacher updates, where decline is monotonic.

We attribute this oscillation to the interaction between EMA lag and the student's exploration. When the student discovers a higher-reward trajectory region, the EMA teacher---lagging by $1/(1-\alpha)$ effective steps---initially provides a KL penalty that pulls the student back toward its recent past, causing a temporary accuracy dip. As the teacher catches up via blending, the KL target aligns with the new behavior, enabling the student to consolidate and push further. This mechanism functions as implicit \emph{learning rate annealing}: the EMA teacher acts as a momentum term that dampens sudden policy shifts while permitting gradual drift.

Gradient norm behavior corroborates this interpretation. Under TT-OPD (v16), gradient norms remain within a stable band ($0.8$--$1.4$) throughout training, whereas hard-copy variants (v12/v13) exhibit gradient spikes at teacher update boundaries that correlate with KL collapse events. The cosine length reward further stabilizes gradients by preventing the response length explosion that would otherwise dominate the loss landscape, keeping the effective gradient focused on task-relevant dimensions rather than length reduction.

\subsection{On-Policy Distillation Instability and Resolution}
\label{sec:opd_instability}

Our ablation trajectory across four OPD variants (v12--v16) reveals a progression of failure modes that aligns closely with the instability patterns identified by Self-Distilled RLVR~\citep{yang26rlsd} and OPSD~\citep{zhao26opsd}, while extending their analysis to the multi-turn agentic setting.

\paragraph{Failure Progression.}
\textbf{(1) Hard-copy teacher (v12, v13):} Periodic hard teacher updates ($T{=}10, 30$) cause catastrophic KL collapse---at each update, the KL divergence drops abruptly (\eg{}, $2.637 \to 0.343$ at step 10 in v12), destroying the distillation gradient signal. This produces monotonic accuracy decline: $56.9\% \to 49.3\%$ over 35 steps in v13, with concurrent multi-turn collapse (validation turns $7.65 \to 5.52$). This mirrors the ``gradient magnitude instability'' diagnosed by \citet{yang26rlsd}, who observe that naive self-distillation produces oscillating gradients that prevent stable learning.
%
\textbf{(2) EMA teacher without privileged conditioning (v14):} Replacing hard updates with EMA blending ($\alpha{=}0.995$) eliminates the KL collapse problem and introduces the oscillating recovery pattern, reaching $53.8\%$ at step 40 (+14.7 pp above frozen-teacher baseline at $39.1\%$). However, validation turns still erode ($7.82 \to 6.23$), indicating multi-turn structure degradation. This confirms RLSD's finding that gradient magnitude control (via EMA) is necessary but insufficient.
%
\textbf{(3) EMA + privileged conditioning without length control (v15):} Adding outcome-privileged teacher conditioning creates an initial accuracy plateau ($54.5\%$, steps 10--20) absent in v14, but response explosion ($11{,}308$ tokens, $91.7\%$ clipping by step 40) destroys the multi-turn structure, collapsing accuracy to $49.0\%$. The privileged conditioning enriches the KL target but accelerates the student's tendency toward verbose single-turn outputs.
%
\textbf{(4) Full TT-OPD (v16):} The addition of cosine length-controlled reward resolves the response explosion, enabling the EMA oscillating recovery to sustain through 65+ steps with accuracy reaching $61.1\%$ (+8.5 pp) while maintaining stable multi-turn structure ($7.0$--$7.4$ turns).

\paragraph{Connection to OPD Literature.}
This failure progression provides empirical grounding for theoretical concerns raised across the OPD literature. \citet{yang26rlsd} propose decomposing the training signal into gradient \emph{magnitude} (controlled by self-distillation) and \emph{direction} (controlled by RLVR); our EMA mechanism serves the magnitude role while outcome-privileged conditioning provides a richer directional signal than generic RLVR. \citet{zhao26opsd} identify teacher staleness as a key failure mode; our hard-copy results (v12/v13) confirm this in the agentic setting, while EMA blending provides a continuous solution. Crucially, our results reveal an additional failure mode \emph{unique to agentic RL}---response explosion and multi-turn collapse---that is absent from single-turn reasoning settings studied by prior OPD work. The cosine length reward addresses this agentic-specific challenge.


% ============================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}
% ============================================================

\paragraph{Model-Agnostic Design.}
\gym{} is designed to be a \emph{playground} for any language model. The Gymnasium interface makes it trivial to swap in different models---from 1.7B parameter models for rapid prototyping to 72B+ models for maximum performance. This democratizes medical AI training by providing a standardized environment rather than a model-specific pipeline.

\paragraph{Tool Diversity and Curriculum Training.}
Our tool usage analysis (Appendix~\ref{app:tool_distribution}) reveals that only 19 of 179 tools (10.6\%) are used during RL training, with extreme Pareto concentration in EHR retrieval tools. This suggests that current reward signals do not incentivize exploration of the full tool space. Tool diversity rewards, curriculum training, and rarity-weighted rewards may address this concentration. Tool-use competence analysis is provided in Appendix~\ref{app:tool_competence}.

\paragraph{Limitations.}
(1) Our current knowledge base, while extensive (828K passages), does not cover all medical subspecialties equally. (2) The simulated patient scenarios, though clinically validated, cannot fully replicate the complexity of real clinical encounters. (3) Safety evaluation relies on rule-based detection rather than expert adjudication for all cases. (4) The extreme tool usage concentration (top 3 tools = 72.9\% of calls) limits generalization claims about broad clinical tool competence.

\paragraph{Ethical Considerations.}
Medical AI systems trained in \gym{} are intended for research purposes. Clinical deployment would require additional validation including prospective clinical studies, regulatory approval, and integration with clinical decision support systems. Our safety-aware reward system is a step toward responsible medical AI but is not a substitute for clinical oversight.


% ============================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
% ============================================================

We identified three compounding failure modes in multi-turn agentic RL---response explosion, multi-turn collapse, and distillation instability---and proposed \textbf{Turn-Level Truncated On-Policy Distillation (TT-OPD)} to address them. Through systematic ablation across four OPD variants, we traced the failure progression from KL collapse (hard-copy teacher) through response explosion (privileged conditioning without length control), connecting our findings to the instability patterns diagnosed by \citet{yang26rlsd} and \citet{zhao26opsd} while identifying multi-turn collapse as a failure mode unique to the agentic setting. The full TT-OPD framework---combining EMA teacher evolution, outcome-privileged conditioning, and cosine length-controlled reward---achieves 61.1\% validation accuracy (+8.5 pp) with stable multi-turn tool use (7.0--7.4 turns) and controlled response length (5.7--9.3K tokens) over 60 steps, while standard GRPO shows no improvement.

We further identify an \emph{agentic-textual transfer gap}: agentic RL improves procedural competence (+22\% composite reward) but does not transfer to text QA due to format reward dilution (24:1 ratio), and only reward normalization (Dr.~GRPO) produces meaningfully different dynamics.

These experiments are grounded in \gym{}, a Gymnasium-compatible environment spanning 10 clinical domains with 195K+ tasks and 187+ tools. Future work should explore adaptive KL coefficients, tighter EMA schedules, and vision-language extensions to push beyond the current accuracy ceiling.

\gym{} is publicly available at \todo{GitHub URL} to facilitate reproducible research in medical AI training.


