\caption{Text QA accuracy across training configurations. Standard agentic RL (GRPO) fails to improve over the SFT baseline (dashed red line), while Dr.~GRPO and direct QA RL (H5, H12) achieve meaningful gains. All successful pathways converge near a $\sim$62\% MedQA ceiling.}
\label{fig:main_results_bar}
\end{figure}


\section{Procedural vs.\ Declarative Analysis}
\label{app:procedural}

While RL does not improve text QA performance, it \emph{does} improve agentic competence---the ability to correctly use clinical tools, retrieve evidence, and reason through multi-step workflows. The composite reward (process quality + accuracy + format) improves by 20\% over 1.4 epochs, demonstrating that RL effectively teaches procedural medical reasoning.

This result reveals a \emph{procedural-declarative dissociation}: RL improves the model's procedural knowledge (how to use tools, when to search, how to structure clinical workflows) without immediately changing its declarative knowledge (medical facts tested by QA benchmarks) \emph{in the standard agentic reward setting}. This parallels findings in cognitive science where procedural and declarative memory systems are neurologically distinct~\citep{squire2004memory}.

Critically, the H5 ablation shows this dissociation is not absolute---when accuracy is the sole reward signal (without format dilution), RL \emph{does} improve declarative knowledge (+1.3 pp MedQA, +0.8 pp MedMCQA on full test sets). This suggests the dissociation is an artifact of reward composition, not a fundamental property of RL.


\section{Tool Usage Distribution}
\label{app:tool_distribution}

We analyze tool call patterns across 23,908 tool invocations during RL training. The distribution reveals an extreme Pareto pattern: of 179 defined tools, only 19 (10.6\%) are ever called, and the top 3 tools account for 72.9\% of all calls (\texttt{get\_lab\_trend}: 31.7\%, \texttt{get\_admission\_info}: 23.0\%, \texttt{get\_lab\_results}: 18.2\%).

Three patterns emerge: (1) \textbf{Domain concentration}---EHR management tools account for 95.6\% of all calls, leaving 7 other domains largely unexplored. (2) \textbf{Read-write asymmetry}---all frequently-used tools are data retrieval operations (\texttt{get\_*}); write/action tools are never called. (3) \textbf{Knowledge tool neglect}---literature search tools (\texttt{search\_pubmed}, \texttt{browse\_article}) are never invoked, suggesting the model relies on parametric knowledge rather than evidence retrieval.


\section{Tool-Use Competence Analysis}
\label{app:tool_competence}

The agentic reward improvement motivates a deeper analysis of what RL actually teaches. We identify four dimensions of tool-use competence: (1) \textbf{Tool Selection Quality}: Does RL improve the model's ability to choose the right tool at the right time? (2) \textbf{Cross-Domain Tool Transfer}: Does tool-use competence learned in one domain transfer to another? (3) \textbf{Process Quality Trajectory}: The 5D reward function provides a multi-dimensional view of competence. (4) \textbf{Multi-Turn Efficiency}: Does RL reduce the number of turns needed to reach a correct answer?

These hypotheses frame tool-use as the primary evaluation axis for agentic RL, complementing the declarative knowledge assessment provided by text QA benchmarks.


